{"title_page": "Gopal Gurung", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Tone|date=December 2018}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=June 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Gopal Gurung \n| image         = Gopal Gurung (2).jpg\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1939|12|07}}\n| birth_place   = [[Darjeeling]], India\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2016|6|10|1935|07|27|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Alka Hospital, [[Patan, Nepal|Lalitpur]], [[Nepal]]\n| residence     = [[Patan, Nepal|Lalitpur]], [[Nepal]]\n| nationality   = [[Nepalis|indian]]\n| education     = M.A. [[Political science]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Kolkata University]]\n| language      = [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[Hindi]] and [[English language|English]]\n}}\n'''Gopal Gurung''' ({{lang-ne| \u0921\u093e.\u0917\u094b\u092a\u093e\u0932 \u0917\u0941\u0930\u0941\u0919}}) (December 07, 1939 \u2013 June 10, 2016) was a Nepali Politician, author, christian missionary ,journalist and futurist of global politics. Gurung encouraged the 'Mongol' groups in Nepal to fight against the Racial discrimination of  [[Hinduism]]  of [[Brahmin]] and [[Kshetris]] ([[Indo-Aryan peoples|Indo-Aryans]]) and create christian nation in asia.<ref name=\"books.google/\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9LiLAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA104&lpg=PA104&dq=Gopal+gurung+against+racial+discrimination&source=bl&ots=1q6XBr4kV8&sig=hAJ1goEboT2zY5qjNUmlfjDGYi4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi0o4KB0MTNAhVLtI8KHeXVChUQ6AEIJzAC#v=onepage&q=Gopal%20gurung%20against%20racial%20discrimination&f=false|title=The Rise of Ethnic Politics in Nepal: Democracy in the Margins}}</ref> He is the founder and president of [[Mongol National Organisation]] (MNO) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/np%7Dmno.html|title=Mongol National Organization|website=www.crwflags.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hangen|first=Susan I.|url=https://books.google.com.np/books?id=dM6MAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT103&lpg=PT103&dq=gopal+gurung+biography&source=bl&ots=0ZjeRLk4mN&sig=ACfU3U2N3f4GN6nEsR4unh9QWDeAES8pdg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiFyMLri9noAhU-4jgGHcqdCc84ChDoATAAegQIDBAm#v=onepage&q=gopal%20gurung%20biography&f=false|title=The Rise of Ethnic Politics in Nepal: Democracy in the Margins|date=2009-12-04|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-18159-8|language=en}}</ref>and the first pioneer of [[republicanism|Republican]] Nepal.<ref name=\"onlinekhabar\">{{cite web |url=http://english.onlinekhabar.com/2016/06/10/379163|title=Gopal Gurung, Nepal\u2019s leading republican figure, dies|publisher=www.onlinekhabar.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/gopal-gurung-nepals-leading-republican-figure-dies.html|title=Gopal Gurung, Nepal\u2019s leading republican figure, dies \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> MNO was established by Gurung on January 1, 1989 when he was in [[Bhadragol]] prison. He wrote the book ''Hidden Facts In Nepalese Politics'', for which he was imprisoned on August 30, 1988.<ref name=\"nepaliliterature\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nepaliliterature.com/uploads/docs/2010121916505111.pdf|title=HIDDEN FACTS IN NEPALESE POLITICS|publisher=www.nepalilterature.com}}</ref>\n\n==Life in Exile==\n'''Gopal Gurung''' is a man of courage who has been the most vocal advocate of the human rights for the indigenous people of [[Nepal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gopalgurung.tripod.com/Theman.html|title=The man, his mission and his works|website=gopalgurung.tripod.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He is an editor and author of many books, the most popular and controversial being The [[Search Results Web results HIDDEN FACTS IN NEPALESE POLITICS|Hidden facts of Nepalese Politics]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nepaliliterature.com/uploads/docs/2010121916505111.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>He was arrested and jailed without any convection or trail by the Panchayat Government in 1989 for being threatened by what he wrote in the \"Hidden Facts in Nepalese Politics.\" The status quote, the Hindu dominated establishment tried all it can to stop Mr. Gurung from speaking against the institutionalized racism, corruptions and exploitation's by the rulers and politicians against the indigenous people who are primarily [[Buddhist]]. But they discovered that it was too late that the genie was already out of the box.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gopalgurung.tripod.com/TelegraphCal.html|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The news of his arrest spread beyond Nepal's border and brought protests and demands of his immediate release. Many local and international journalists, writers and organizations such as [[PEN London]], [[Press Foundation of Asia]], [[Amnesty International]], and Denmark on [[Human Rights]] raised their voices on behalf of Mr. Gurung which eventually led to his release after the democracy came into existence. Mr. Gurung holds MA in Political Science, and has been an '''Editor-in-Chief''' and '''Publisher''' of the ''\"New-light\"'' and ''\"Thunderbolt\"'' in Kathmandu. He is an ex-member of the '''Nepal Journalist Association''', Central Committee, Ex-General Secretary of the ''[[World Nepalese Association]]'' and Chairman of ''[[Press Council of India|All India Journalist Council]]'' for [[Nepal]]. He is also a '''Consultant and coordinator''' for the [[Press Foundation of Asia]] (PFA), [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gopalgurung.tripod.com/Theman.html|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Gopal Gurung]] has the tenacity and determination to fight for what he believes is the right. He has risked his life to fight for his people in [[Nepal]], but his unwavering courage has come at a price. He was kept at a minimum subsistence while he was in prison: 700 grams of coarse rice and four rupees (about 10 cents) a day as an allowance. Furthermore, he was kept with all the criminals, and he was denied visitation and food for many days for merely writing about the pervasive reality and demanding answers on [[Human rights]] and [[justice]]. Though he is a free man now, he still receives obscene phone calls and death threats. But despite all odds, he continues to fight for the [[equality before the law|equal rights]] and justice for all the Nepalese. His works has already ignited political and social activism especially among the [[Mongol]] People. Because of his contribution the people of [[Nepal]] are politically conscious than ever before. [[Gopal Gurung]] and his followers have founded [[Mongol National Organisation|Mongol National Organization]] through which they hope to bring the equality and desperately needed change in [[Nepal]]. [[PEN International|PEN London]], [[Press Foundation of Asia]], [[Amnesty International]], and Denmark on [[Human rights|Human Rights]].The following excerpts are just a few drops of a pond. It shows how the present world responded on humanistic ground towards the good cause of a [[freedom fighter]]. They know Gopal Gurung's struggle in not communal one, and their support is for [[universality (philosophy)|universally]] approved human rights, [[democracy]] and [[freedom]]. So, '''Hidden facts in Nepalese Politics''' are a short of pavement for the [[Manifesto]] of this newly formed political organization, [[Mongol National Organisation|Mongol National Organization]].\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''collections'''\n\n* Shesh-kavita (poems): published in 1962.\n* Shesh-yatra (novel) published in 1965\n* Shesh-pran (stories) published in 1965\n* Shesh-prashna (stories) published in 1965\n\n'''Books on politics'''\n\n* Nepali Rajnitima Adhekha Sachai (Hidden Facts in Nepalese Politics) Nepali edition published in Nepali 1985, 1988, 1993 &  English edition in 1994. \n* Newly Created Untouchable Janjaati (nomad, gypsy) Society in Nepalese and Sikkimese Politics, published thrice in 1998 and its English edition in 1999. \n* In Quest of Mongol Entity, and Doctorate (PhD) on MNO, Nepali edition published in March 2001. English edition in July 2001 \n* Mongolism-Bahunism-Maoism in Nepalese Politics, published in Nepali  2006  Also prepared in English.\n\n<br />\n\n==Death==\n\n==Reference==\n\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Tone|date=December 2018}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=June 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Gopal Gurung \n| image         = Gopal Gurung (2).jpg\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1939|12|07}}\n| birth_place   = [[Darjeeling]], India\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2016|6|10|1935|07|27|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Alka Hospital, [[Patan, Nepal|Lalitpur]], [[Nepal]]\n| residence     = [[Patan, Nepal|Lalitpur]], [[Nepal]]\n| nationality   = [[Nepalis|indian]]\n| education     = M.A. [[Political science]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Kolkata University]]\n| language      = [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[Hindi]] and [[English language|English]]\n}}\n'''Gopal Gurung''' ({{lang-ne| \u0921\u093e.\u0917\u094b\u092a\u093e\u0932 \u0917\u0941\u0930\u0941\u0919}}) (December 07, 1939 \u2013 June 10, 2016) was a Nepali Politician, author, journalist and futurist of global politics. Gurung encouraged the 'Mongol' groups in Nepal to fight against the Racial discrimination of  [[Hinduism]]  of [[Brahmin]] and [[Kshetris]] ([[Indo-Aryan peoples|Indo-Aryans]]).<ref name=\"books.google/\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9LiLAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA104&lpg=PA104&dq=Gopal+gurung+against+racial+discrimination&source=bl&ots=1q6XBr4kV8&sig=hAJ1goEboT2zY5qjNUmlfjDGYi4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi0o4KB0MTNAhVLtI8KHeXVChUQ6AEIJzAC#v=onepage&q=Gopal%20gurung%20against%20racial%20discrimination&f=false|title=The Rise of Ethnic Politics in Nepal: Democracy in the Margins}}</ref> He is the founder and president of [[Mongol National Organisation]] (MNO) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/np%7Dmno.html|title=Mongol National Organization|website=www.crwflags.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hangen|first=Susan I.|url=https://books.google.com.np/books?id=dM6MAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT103&lpg=PT103&dq=gopal+gurung+biography&source=bl&ots=0ZjeRLk4mN&sig=ACfU3U2N3f4GN6nEsR4unh9QWDeAES8pdg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiFyMLri9noAhU-4jgGHcqdCc84ChDoATAAegQIDBAm#v=onepage&q=gopal%20gurung%20biography&f=false|title=The Rise of Ethnic Politics in Nepal: Democracy in the Margins|date=2009-12-04|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-18159-8|language=en}}</ref>and the first pioneer of [[republicanism|Republican]] Nepal.<ref name=\"onlinekhabar\">{{cite web |url=http://english.onlinekhabar.com/2016/06/10/379163|title=Gopal Gurung, Nepal\u2019s leading republican figure, dies|publisher=www.onlinekhabar.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/gopal-gurung-nepals-leading-republican-figure-dies.html|title=Gopal Gurung, Nepal\u2019s leading republican figure, dies \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> MNO was established by Gurung on January 1, 1989 when he was in [[Bhadragol]] prison. He wrote the book ''Hidden Facts In Nepalese Politics'', for which he was imprisoned on August 30, 1988.<ref name=\"nepaliliterature\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nepaliliterature.com/uploads/docs/2010121916505111.pdf|title=HIDDEN FACTS IN NEPALESE POLITICS|publisher=www.nepalilterature.com}}</ref>\n\n==Life in Exile==\n'''Gopal Gurung''' is a man of courage who has been the most vocal advocate of the human rights for the indigenous people of [[Nepal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gopalgurung.tripod.com/Theman.html|title=The man, his mission and his works|website=gopalgurung.tripod.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He is an editor and author of many books, the most popular and controversial being The [[Search Results Web results HIDDEN FACTS IN NEPALESE POLITICS|Hidden facts of Nepalese Politics]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nepaliliterature.com/uploads/docs/2010121916505111.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>He was arrested and jailed without any convection or trail by the Panchayat Government in 1989 for being threatened by what he wrote in the \"Hidden Facts in Nepalese Politics.\" The status quote, the Hindu dominated establishment tried all it can to stop Mr. Gurung from speaking against the institutionalized racism, corruptions and exploitation's by the rulers and politicians against the indigenous people who are primarily [[Buddhist]]. But they discovered that it was too late that the genie was already out of the box.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gopalgurung.tripod.com/TelegraphCal.html|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The news of his arrest spread beyond Nepal's border and brought protests and demands of his immediate release. Many local and international journalists, writers and organizations such as [[PEN London]], [[Press Foundation of Asia]], [[Amnesty International]], and Denmark on [[Human Rights]] raised their voices on behalf of Mr. Gurung which eventually led to his release after the democracy came into existence. Mr. Gurung holds MA in Political Science, and has been an '''Editor-in-Chief''' and '''Publisher''' of the ''\"New-light\"'' and ''\"Thunderbolt\"'' in Kathmandu. He is an ex-member of the '''Nepal Journalist Association''', Central Committee, Ex-General Secretary of the ''[[World Nepalese Association]]'' and Chairman of ''[[Press Council of India|All India Journalist Council]]'' for [[Nepal]]. He is also a '''Consultant and coordinator''' for the [[Press Foundation of Asia]] (PFA), [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gopalgurung.tripod.com/Theman.html|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Gopal Gurung]] has the tenacity and determination to fight for what he believes is the right. He has risked his life to fight for his people in [[Nepal]], but his unwavering courage has come at a price. He was kept at a minimum subsistence while he was in prison: 700 grams of coarse rice and four rupees (about 10 cents) a day as an allowance. Furthermore, he was kept with all the criminals, and he was denied visitation and food for many days for merely writing about the pervasive reality and demanding answers on [[Human rights]] and [[justice]]. Though he is a free man now, he still receives obscene phone calls and death threats. But despite all odds, he continues to fight for the [[equality before the law|equal rights]] and justice for all the Nepalese. His works has already ignited political and social activism especially among the [[Mongol]] People. Because of his contribution the people of [[Nepal]] are politically conscious than ever before. [[Gopal Gurung]] and his followers have founded [[Mongol National Organisation|Mongol National Organization]] through which they hope to bring the equality and desperately needed change in [[Nepal]]. [[PEN International|PEN London]], [[Press Foundation of Asia]], [[Amnesty International]], and Denmark on [[Human rights|Human Rights]].The following excerpts are just a few drops of a pond. It shows how the present world responded on humanistic ground towards the good cause of a [[freedom fighter]]. They know Gopal Gurung's struggle in not communal one, and their support is for [[universality (philosophy)|universally]] approved human rights, [[democracy]] and [[freedom]]. So, '''Hidden facts in Nepalese Politics''' are a short of pavement for the [[Manifesto]] of this newly formed political organization, [[Mongol National Organisation|Mongol National Organization]].\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''collections'''\n\n* Shesh-kavita (poems): published in 1962.\n* Shesh-yatra (novel) published in 1965\n* Shesh-pran (stories) published in 1965\n* Shesh-prashna (stories) published in 1965\n\n'''Books on politics'''\n\n* Nepali Rajnitima Adhekha Sachai (Hidden Facts in Nepalese Politics) Nepali edition published in Nepali 1985, 1988, 1993 &  English edition in 1994. \n* Newly Created Untouchable Janjaati (nomad, gypsy) Society in Nepalese and Sikkimese Politics, published thrice in 1998 and its English edition in 1999. \n* In Quest of Mongol Entity, and Doctorate (PhD) on MNO, Nepali edition published in March 2001. English edition in July 2001 \n* Mongolism-Bahunism-Maoism in Nepalese Politics, published in Nepali  2006  Also prepared in English.\n\n<br />\n\n==Death==\n\n==Reference==\n\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "202.51.70.237", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gopal_Gurung"}
{"title_page": "Rampurwa, Parasi", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Rampurwa\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0930\u093e\u092e\u092a\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0935\u093e\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             =\n|image_seal             =\n|image_map              = <!-- NepalNawalparasiDistrictmap.png -->\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Map of the village development committees in Nawalparasi District\n|pushpin_map            = <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        =340\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Nepal\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Nepal}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Zones of Nepal|Zone]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Lumbini Zone]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Nepal|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Nawalparasi District]]\n|<!-- Politics -->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      = <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    -->\n|unit_pref                =  <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   -->\n|population_as_of               = 1991\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 8820\n|population_density_km2         = auto\n|population_blank1_title        = Ethnicities\n<!-- General information  -->\n|timezone               = [[Nepal Time]]\n|utc_offset             = +5:45\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Rampurwa ''' is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Nawalparasi District]] in the [[Lumbini Zone]] of southern [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[1991 Nepal census]] it had a population of 3689 people living in 542 individual households.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1|title=Nepal Census 2001|work=Nepal's Village Development Committees|publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]]|accessdate=18 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Parasi District}}\n\n{{coord|29|13|N|80|58|E|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Parasi District]]\n\n{{Province5NP-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Rampurwa\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0930\u093e\u092e\u092a\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0935\u093e\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             